{
  "text": "R-VSD is usually treated surgically or by percutaneous transcatheter closure. It would have been difficult to use conventional percutaneous transcatheter closure in this patient for two reasons: the unusual shape of the R-VSD (at a 135\u00b0 angle with the G-T VG) would have complicated the placement and adjustment of an appropriate occluder by the usual transcatheter route; and second, the femoral artery in a low body weight child, such as this patient, is too small and thin to accommodate a large sheath. Furthermore, repeat thoracotomy surgery imposes significant trauma, and is not without risk [CITATION_1] ]. Therefore, a TEE-guided minimally invasive surgical device closure was planned.",
